Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: Existing semi-supervised object detection (SSOD) methods struggle with the inherent noise in pseudo-labeled bounding boxes, especially when both classification and localization uncertainties are entangled during training. While prior works like certainty-aware pseudo labeling (Paper 1) and dual decoupling frameworks (Paper 2) have made strides by separately modeling classification and localization quality or splitting clean/noisy samples, they still rely heavily on fixed or threshold-based heuristics that may not adapt well across datasets or model states. Moreover, these approaches often treat uncertainty as a post-hoc filtering mechanism rather than an integrated learning signal. My key insight is that instead of merely decoupling tasks or data paths, we should *learn to disentangle uncertainty at the feature level*—specifically, by explicitly modeling the divergence between classification and localization confidence through a meta-decoupling module that dynamically identifies and isolates noisy pseudo-boxes based on their epistemic uncertainty. This leads to a novel framework where uncertainty is not just estimated but actively used to reweight, refine, and route pseudo-labels through specialized subnetworks. Unlike previous dual-decoupling methods that use static thresholds or auxiliary heads, our approach introduces a learnable uncertainty gate that modulates information flow based on online uncertainty estimation, enabling adaptive separation of clean and noisy supervision without rigid binning. Furthermore, this method integrates uncertainty calibration into the training loop via a contrastive regularization term that encourages distinct representations for high- and low-confidence regions, enhancing generalization under label scarcity.

